Alteration.def: Modifying the anatomic structure of a body part without affecting the function of the body part
Alteration.exp: Principal purpose is to improve appearance

Bypass.def: Altering the route of passage of the contents of a tubular body part
Bypass.exp: Rerouting contents of a body part to a downstream area of the normal route, to a similar route and body part, or to an abnormal route and dissimilar body part. Includes one or more anastomoses, with or without the use of a device

Change.def: Taking out or off a device from a body part and putting back an identical or similar device in or on the same body part without cutting or puncturing the skin or a mucous membrane
Change.exp: All CHANGE procedures are coded using the approach EXTERNAL
Change.inc: Urinary catheter change, gastrostomy tube change

Control.def: Stopping, or attempting to stop, postprocedural or other acute bleeding
Control.inc: Control of post-prostatectomy hemorrhage, control of intracranial subdural hemorrhage, control of bleeding duodenal ulcer, control of retroperitoneal hemorrhage

Creation.def: Putting in or on biological or synthetic material to form a new body part that to the extent possible replicates the anatomic structure or function of an absent body part
Creation.exp: Used for gender reassignment surgery and corrective procedures in individuals with congenital anomalies
Creation.inc: Creation of vagina in a male, creation of right and left atrioventricular valve from common atrioventricular valve

Destruction.def: Physical eradication of all or a portion of a body part by the direct use of energy, force, or a destructive agent
Destruction.exp: None of the body part is physically taken out
Destruction.inc: Fulguration of rectal polyp, cautery of skin lesion

Detachment.def: Cutting off all or a portion of the upper or lower extremities
Detachment.exp: The body part value is the site of the detachment, with a qualifier if applicable to further specify the level where the extremity was detached
Detachment.inc: Below knee amputation, disarticulation of shoulder

Dilation.def: Expanding an orifice or the lumen of a tubular body part
Dilation.exp: The orifice can be a natural orifice or an artificially created orifice. Accomplished by stretching a tubular body part using intraluminal pressure or by cutting part of the orifice or wall of the tubular body part

Division.def: Cutting into a body part, without draining fluids and/or gases from the body part, in order to separate or transect a body part
Division.exp: All or a portion of the body part is separated into two or more portions

Drainage.def: Taking or letting out fluids and/or gases from a body part
Drainage.exp: The qualifier DIAGNOSTIC is used to identify drainage procedures that are biopsies

Excision.def: Cutting out or off, without replacement, a portion of a body part
Excision.exp: The qualifier DIAGNOSTIC is used to identify excision procedures that are biopsies

Extirpation.def: Taking or cutting out solid matter from a body part
Extirpation.exp: The solid matter may be an abnormal byproduct of a biological function or a foreign body; it may be imbedded in a body part or in the lumen of a tubular body part. The solid matter may or may not have been previously broken into pieces

Extraction.def: Pulling or stripping out or off all or a portion of a body part by the use of force
Extraction.exp: The qualifier DIAGNOSTIC is used to identify extraction procedures that are biopsies

Fragmentation.def: Breaking solid matter in a body part into pieces
Fragmentation.exp: Physical force (e.g., manual, ultrasonic) applied directly or indirectly is used to break the solid matter into pieces. The solid matter may be an abnormal byproduct of a biological function or a foreign body. The pieces of solid matter are not taken out

Fusion.def: Joining together portions of an articular body part rendering the articular body part immobile
Fusion.exp: The body part is joined together by fixation device, bone graft, or other means

Insertion.def: Putting in a nonbiological appliance that monitors, assists, performs, or prevents a physiological function but does not physically take the place of a body part
Insertion.inc: Insertion of radioactive implant, insertion of central venous catheter

Inspection.def: Visually and/or manually exploring a body part
Inspection.exp: Visual exploration may be performed with or without optical instrumentation. Manual exploration may be performed directly or through intervening body layers

Map.def: Locating the route of passage of electrical impulses and/or locating functional areas in a body part
Map.exp: Applicable only to the cardiac conduction mechanism and the central nervous system

Occlusion.def: Completely closing an orifice or the lumen of a tubular body part
Occlusion.exp: The orifice can be a natural orifice or an artificially created orifice
Occlusion.inc: Fallopian tube ligation, ligation of inferior vena cava

Reattachment.def: Putting back in or on all or a portion of a separated body part to its normal location or other suitable location
Reattachment.exp: Vascular circulation and nervous pathways may or may not be reestablished
Reattachment.inc: Reattachment of hand, reattachment of avulsed kidney

Release.def: Freeing a body part from an abnormal physical constraint by cutting or by the use of force
Release.exp: Some of the restraining tissue may be taken out but none of the body part is taken out

Removal.def: Taking out or off a device from a body part
Removal.exp: If a device is taken out and a similar device put in without cutting or puncturing the skin or mucous membrane, the procedure is coded to the root operation CHANGE. Otherwise, the procedure for taking out a device is coded to the root operation REMOVAL
Removal.inc: Drainage tube removal, cardiac pacemaker removal

Repair.def: Restoring, to the extent possible, a body part to its normal anatomic structure and function
Repair.exp: Used only when the method to accomplish the repair is not one of the other root operations

Replacement.def: Putting in or on biological or synthetic material that physically takes the place and/or function of all or a portion of a body part
Replacement.exp: The body part may have been taken out or replaced, or may be taken out, physically eradicated, or rendered nonfunctional during the Replacement procedure. A Removal procedure is coded for taking out the device used in a previous replacement procedure
Replacement.inc: Total hip replacement, bone graft, free skin graft

Reposition.def: Moving to its normal location, or other suitable location, all or a portion of a body part
Reposition.exp: The body part is moved to a new location from an abnormal location, or from a normal location where it is not functioning correctly. The body part may or may not be cut out or off to be moved to the new location
Reposition.inc: Reposition of undescended testicle, fracture reduction

Resection.def: Cutting out or off, without replacement, all of a body part
Resection.inc: Total nephrectomy, total lobectomy of lung

Restriction.def: Partially closing an orifice or the lumen of a tubular body part
Restriction.exp: The orifice can be a natural orifice or an artificially created orifice

Revision.def: Correcting, to the extent possible, a portion of a malfunctioning device or the position of a displaced device
Revision.exp: Revision can include correcting a malfunctioning or displaced device by taking out or putting in components of the device such as a screw or pin
Revision.inc: Adjustment of position of pacemaker lead, recementing of hip prosthesis

Supplement.def: Putting in or on biological or synthetic material that physically reinforces and/or augments the function of a portion of a body part
Supplement.exp: The biological material is non-living, or is living and from the same individual. The body part may have been previously replaced, and the Supplement procedure is performed to physically reinforce and/or augment the function of the replaced body part
Supplement.inc: Herniorrhaphy using mesh, mitral valve ring annuloplasty, put a new acetabular liner in a previous hip replacement

Transfer.def: Moving, without taking out, all or a portion of a body part to another location to take over the function of all or a portion of a body part
Transfer.exp: The body part transferred remains connected to its vascular and nervous supply
Transfer.inc: Tendon transfer, skin pedicle flap transfer

Transplantation.def: Putting in or on all or a portion of a living body part taken from another individual or animal to physically take the place and/or function of all or a portion of a similar body part
Transplantation.exp: The native body part may or may not be taken out, and the transplanted body part may take over all or a portion of its function

Device Fitting.def: Fitting of a device designed to facilitate or support achievement of a higher level of function

Hearing Aid Assessment.def: Measurement of the appropriateness and/or effectiveness of a hearing device

Hearing Assessment.def: Measurement of hearing and related functions

Hearing Treatment.def: Application of techniques to improve, augment, or compensate for hearing and related functional impairment

Motor and/or Nerve Function Assessment.def: Measurement of motor, nerve, and related functions

Motor Treatment.def: Exercise or activities to increase or facilitate motor function

Speech Assessment.def: Measurement of speech and related functions

Speech Treatment.def: Application of techniques to improve, augment, or compensate for speech and related functional impairment

Vestibular Assessment.def: Measurement of the vestibular system and related functions

Vestibular Treatment.def: Application of techniques to improve, augment, or compensate for vestibular and related functional impairment

Acoustic Reflex Decay.def: Measures reduction in size/strength of acoustic reflex over time

Acoustic Reflex Patterns.def: Defines site of lesion based upon presence/absence of acoustic reflexes with ipsilateral vs. contralateral stimulation

Acoustic Reflex Threshold.def: Determines minimal intensity that acoustic reflex occurs with ipsilateral and/or contralateral stimulation

Aerobic Capacity and Endurance.def: Measures autonomic responses to positional changes; perceived exertion, dyspnea or angina during activity; performance during exercise protocols; standard vital signs; and blood gas analysis or oxygen consumption

Alternate Binaural or Monaural Loudness.def: Determines auditory stimulus parameter that yields the same objective sensation
Alternate Binaural or Monaural Loudness.inc: Sound intensities that yield same loudness perception

Anthropometric Characteristics.def: Measures edema, body fat composition, height, weight, length and girth

Aphasia (Assessment).def: Measures expressive and receptive speech and language function including reading and writing

Aphasia (Treatment).def: Applying techniques to improve, augment, or compensate for receptive/ expressive language impairments

Articulation/Phonology (Treatment).def: Applying techniques to correct, improve, or compensate for speech productive impairment

Assistive Listening Device.def: Assists in use of effective and appropriate assistive listening device/system

Assistive Listening System/Device Select.def: Measures the effectiveness and appropriateness of assistive listening systems/devices

Auditory Evoked Potentials.def: Measures electric responses produced by the VIIIth cranial nerve and brainstem following auditory stimulation

Auditory Processing (Assessment).def: Evaluates ability to receive and process auditory information and comprehension of spoken language

Auditory Processing (Treatment).def: Applying techniques to improve the receiving and processing of auditory information and comprehension of spoken language

Augmentative/Alternative Communication S.def: Determines the appropriateness of aids, techniques, symbols, and/or strategies to augment or replace speech and enhance communication
Augmentative/Alternative Communication S.inc: Includes the use of telephones, writing equipment, emergency equipment, and TDD

Aural Rehabilitation.def: Applying techniques to improve the communication abilities associated with hearing loss

Aural Rehabilitation Status.def: Measures impact of a hearing loss including evaluation of receptive and expressive communication skills

Bathing/Showering Techniques.def: Activities to facilitate obtaining and using supplies, soaping, rinsing and drying body parts, maintaining bathing position, and transferring to and from bathing positions

Bed Mobility (Treatment).def: Exercise or activities to facilitate transitional movements within bed

Bekesy Audiometry.def: Uses an instrument that provides a choice of discrete or continuously varying pure tones; choice of pulsed or continuous signal

Binaural Electroacoustic Hearing Aid Che.def: Determines mechanical and electroacoustic function of bilateral hearing aids using hearing aid test box

Binaural Hearing Aid (Assessment).def: Measures the candidacy, effectiveness, and appropriateness of a hearing aids

Bithermal, Binaural Caloric Irrigation.def: Measures the rhythmic eye movements stimulated by changing the temperature of the vestibular system

Bithermal, Monaural Caloric Irrigation.def: Measures the rhythmic eye movements stimulated by changing the temperature of the vestibular system in one ear

Cerumen Management.def: Includes examination of external auditory canal and tympanic membrane and removal of cerumen from external ear canal

Cochlear Implant Rehabilitation.def: Applying techniques to improve the communication abilities of individuals with cochlear implant; includes programming the device, providing patients/families with information

Communicative/Cognitive Integration Skil.def: Measures ability to use higher cortical functions
Communicative/Cognitive Integration Skil.inc: Includes orientation, recognition, attention span, initiation and termination of activity, memory, sequencing, categorizing, concept formation, spatial operations, judgment, problem solving, generalization and pragmatic communication

Communicative/Cognitive Integration Skil.def: Activities to facilitate the use of higher cortical functions
Communicative/Cognitive Integration Skil.inc: Includes level of arousal, orientation, recognition, attention span, initiation and termination of activity, memory sequencing,  judgment and problem solving, learning and generalization, and pragmatic communication

Computerized Dynamic Posturography.def: Measures the status of the peripheral and central vestibular system and the sensory/motor component of balance; evaluates the efficacy of vestibular rehabilitation

Conditioned Play Audiometry.def: Behavioral measures using nonspeech and speech stimuli to obtain frequency-specific and ear-specific information on auditory status from the patient
Conditioned Play Audiometry.exp: Obtains speech reception threshold by having patient point to pictures of spondaic words

Coordination/Dexterity (Assessment).def: Measures large and small muscle groups for controlled goal- directed movements

Coordination/Dexterity (Treatment).def: Exercise or activities to facilitate gross coordination and fine coordination

Cranial Nerve Integrity.def: Measures cranial nerve sensory and motor functions, including tastes, smell and facial expression

Dressing Techniques.def: Activities to facilitate selecting clothing and accessories, dressing and undressing, adjusting clothing and shoes, applying and removing devices, prostheses or orthoses

Ear Protector Attentuation.def: Measures ear protector fit and effectiveness

Electrocochleography.def: Measures the VIIIth cranial nerve action potential

Environmental, Home and Work Barriers.def: Measures current and potential barriers to optimal function, including safety hazards, access problems and home or office design

Ergonomics and Body Mechanics.def: Ergonomic measurement of job tasks, work hardening or work conditioning needs; functional capacity; and body mechanics

Eustachian Tube Function.def: Measures eustachian tube function and patency of eustachian tube

Evoked Otoacoustic Emissions, Diagnostic.def: Measures auditory evoked potentials in a diagnostic format

Evoked Otoacoustic Emissions, Screening.def: Measures auditory evoked potentials in a screening format

Facial Nerve Function.def: Measures electrical activity of the VIIth cranial nerve (facial nerve)

Feeding/Eating (Treatment).def: Exercise or activities to facilitate setting up food, selecting and using utensils and tableware, bringing food or drink to mouth, cleaning face, hands, and clothing, and management of alternative methods of nourishment

Filtered Speech.def: Uses high or low pass filtered speech stimuli to assess central auditory processing disorders, site of lesion testing

Fluency (Treatment).def: Applying techniques to improve and augment fluent speech

Gait and/or Balance.def: Measures biomechanical, arthrokinematic and other spatial and temporal characteristics of gait and balance

Gait Training/Functional Ambulation.def: Exercise or activities to facilitate ambulation on a variety of surfaces and in a variety of environments

Grooming/Personal Hygiene (Treatment).def: Activities to facilitate obtaining and using supplies in a sequential fashion: general grooming, oral hygiene, toilet hygiene, cleaning body, and personal care devices, including artificial airways

Hearing and Related Disorders Counseling.def: Provides patients/families/caregivers with information, support, referrals to facilitate recovery from a communication disorder
Hearing and Related Disorders Counseling.inc: Includes strategies for psychosocial adjustment to hearing loss for clients and families/caregivers

Hearing and Related Disorders Prevention.def: Provides patients/families/caregivers with information and support to prevent communication disorders

Hearing Screening.def: Pass/refer measures designed to identify need for further audiologic assessment

Home Management (Assessment).def: Obtaining and maintaining personal and household possessions and environment
Home Management (Assessment).inc: Includes clothing care, cleaning, meal preparation and cleanup, shopping, money management, household maintenance, safety procedures, and childcare/parenting

Home Management (Treatment).def: Activities to facilitate obtaining and maintaining personal household possessions and environment
Home Management (Treatment).inc: Includes clothing care, cleaning, meal preparation and clean-up, shopping, money management, household maintenance, safety procedures, childcare/parenting

Instrumental Swallowing and Oral Functio.def: Measures swallowing function using instrumental diagnostic procedures
Instrumental Swallowing and Oral Functio.exp: Methods include videofluoroscopy, ultrasound, manometry, endoscopy

Manual Therapy Techniques.def: Techniques in which the therapist uses his/her hands to administer skilled movements
Manual Therapy Techniques.inc: Includes connective tissue massage, joint mobilization and manipulation, manual lymph drainage, manual traction, soft tissue mobilization and manipulation

Monaural Electroacoustic Hearing Aid Che.def: Determines mechanical and electroacoustic function of one hearing aid using hearing aid test box

Monaural Hearing Aid (Assessment).def: Measures the candidacy, effectiveness, and appropriateness of a hearing aid

Motor Function (Assessment).def: Measures the body's functional and versatile movement patterns
Motor Function (Assessment).inc: Includes motor assessment scales, analysis of head, trunk and limb movement, and assessment of motor learning

Motor Function (Treatment).def: Exercise or activities to facilitate crossing midline, laterality, bilateral integration, praxis, neuromuscular relaxation, inhibition, facilitation, motor function and motor learning

Motor Speech (Assessment).def: Measures neurological motor aspects of speech production

Motor Speech (Treatment).def: Applying techniques to improve and augment the impaired neurological motor aspects of speech production

Muscle Performance (Assessment).def: Measures muscle strength, power and endurance using manual testing, dynamometry or computer-assisted electromechanical muscle test; functional muscle strength, power and endurance; muscle pain, tone, or soreness; or pelvic-floor musculature
Muscle Performance (Assessment).exp: Muscle endurance refers to the ability to contract a muscle repeatedly over time

Muscle Performance (Treatment).def: Exercise or activities to increase the capacity of a muscle to do work in terms of strength, power, and/or endurance
Muscle Performance (Treatment).exp: Muscle strength is the force exerted to overcome resistance in one maximal effort. Muscle power is work produced per unit of time, or the product of strength and speed. Muscle endurance is the ability to contract a muscle repeatedly over time

Neuromotor Development.def: Measures motor development, righting and equilibrium reactions, and reflex and equilibrium reactions

Non-invasive Instrumental Status.def: Instrumental measures of oral, nasal, vocal, and velopharyngeal functions as they pertain to speech production

Nonspoken Language (Assessment).def: Measures nonspoken language (print, sign, symbols) for communication

Nonspoken Language (Treatment).def: Applying techniques that improve, augment, or compensate spoken communication

Oral Peripheral Mechanism.def: Structural measures of face, jaw, lips, tongue, teeth, hard and soft palate, pharynx as related to speech production

Orofacial Myofunctional (Assessment).def: Measures orofacial myofunctional patterns for speech and related functions

Orofacial Myofunctional (Treatment).def: Applying techniques to improve, alter, or augment impaired orofacial myofunctional patterns and related speech production errors

Pain.def: Measures muscle soreness, pain and soreness with joint movement, and pain perception
Pain.inc: Includes questionnaires, graphs, symptom magnification scales or visual analog scales

Perceptual Processing (Assessment).def: Measures stereognosis, kinesthesia, body schema, right-left discrimination, form constancy, position in space, visual closure, figure-ground, depth perception, spatial relations and topographical orientation

Perceptual Processing (Treatment).def: Exercise and activities to facilitate perceptual processing
Perceptual Processing (Treatment).exp: Includes stereognosis, kinesthesia, body schema, right-left discrimination, form constancy, position in space, visual closure, figure-ground, depth perception, spatial relations, and topographical orientation
Perceptual Processing (Treatment).inc: Includes stereognosis, kinesthesia, body schema, right-left discrimination, form constancy, position in space, visual closure, figure-ground, depth perception, spatial relations, and topographical orientation

Performance Intensity Phonetically Balan.def: Measures word recognition over varying intensity levels

Postural Control.def: Exercise or activities to increase postural alignment and control

Prosthesis.def: Artificial substitutes for missing body parts that augment performance or function

Psychosocial Skills (Assessment).def: The ability to interact in society and to process emotions
Psychosocial Skills (Assessment).inc: Includes psychological (values, interests, self-concept); social (role performance, social conduct, interpersonal skills, self expression); self-management (coping skills, time management, self-control)

Psychosocial Skills (Treatment).def: The ability to interact in society and to process emotions
Psychosocial Skills (Treatment).inc: Includes psychological (values, interests, self-concept); social (role performance, social conduct, interpersonal skills, self expression); self-management (coping skills, time management, self-control)

Pure Tone Audiometry, Air.def: Air-conduction pure tone threshold measures with appropriate masking

Pure Tone Audiometry, Air and Bone.def: Air-conduction and bone-conduction pure tone threshold measures with appropriate masking

Pure Tone Stenger.def: Measures unilateral nonorganic hearing loss based on simultaneous presentation of pure tones of differing volume

Range of Motion and Joint Integrity.def: Measures quantity, quality, grade, and classification of joint movement and/or mobility
Range of Motion and Joint Integrity.exp: Range of Motion is the space, distance or angle through which movement occurs at a joint or series of joints.  Joint integrity is the conformance of joints to expected anatomic, biomechanical and kinematic norms

Range of Motion and Joint Mobility.def: Exercise or activities to increase muscle length and joint mobility

Receptive/Expressive Language (Treatment.def: Applying techniques tot improve and augment receptive/expressive language

Reflex Integrity.def: Measures the presence, absence, or exaggeration of developmentally appropriate, pathologic or normal reflexes

Select Picture Audiometry.def: Establishes hearing threshold levels for speech using pictures

Sensorineural Acuity Level.def: Measures sensorineural acuity masking presented via bone conduction

Sensory Aids.def: Determines the appropriateness of a sensory prosthetic device, other than a hearing aid or assistive listening system/device

Short Increment Sensitivity Index.def: Measures the ear's ability to detect small intensity changes; site of lesion test requiring a behavioral response

Somatosensory Evoked Potentials.def: Measures neural activity from sites throughout the body

Speech and/or Language Screening.def: Identifies need for further speech and/or language evaluation

Speech Threshold.def: Measures minimal intensity needed to repeat spondaic words

Speech-Language Pathology and Related Di.def: Provides patients/families with information, support, referrals to facilitate recovery from a communication disorder
Applying techniques to avoid or minimize onset and/or development of a communication disorder

Speech/Word Recognition.def: Measures ability to repeat/identify single syllable words; scores given as a percentage; includes word recognition/speech discrimination

Staggered Spondaic Word.def: Measures central auditory processing site of lesion based upon dichotic presentation of spondaic words

Stenger.def: Measures unilateral nonorganic hearing loss based on simultaneous presentation of signals of differing volume

Swallowing Dysfunction.def: Activities to improve swallowing function in coordination with respiratory function
Swallowing Dysfunction.inc: Includes function and coordination of sucking, mastication, coughing, swallowing

Synthetic Sentence Identification.def: Measures central auditory dysfunction using identification of third order approximations of sentences and competing messages

Therapeutic Exercise.def: Exercise or activities to facilitate sensory awareness, sensory processing, sensory integration, balance training, conditioning, reconditioning
Therapeutic Exercise.inc: Includes developmental activities, breathing exercises, aerobic endurance activities, aquatic exercises, stretching and ventilatory muscle training

Tone Decay.def: Measures decrease in hearing sensitivity to a tone; site of lesion test requiring a behavioral response

Transfer.def: Transitional movement from one surface to another

Transfer Training.def: Exercise or activities to facilitate movement from one surface to another

Tympanometry.def: Measures the integrity of the middle ear; measures ease at which sound flows through the tympanic membrane while air pressure against the membrane is varied

Unithermal Binaural Screen.def: Measures the rhythmic eye movements stimulated by changing the temperature of the vestibular system  in both ears using warm water, screening format

Ventilation, Respiration and Circulation.def: Measures ventilatory muscle strength, power and endurance, pulmonary function and ventilatory mechanics
Ventilation, Respiration and Circulation.inc: Includes ability to clear airway, activities that aggravate or relieve edema, pain, dyspnea or other symptoms, chest wall mobility, cardiopulmonary response to performance of ADL and IAD, cough and sputum, standard vital signs

Vestibular.def: Applying techniques to compensate for balance disorders; includes habituation, exercise therapy, and balance retraining

Visual Motor Integration (Assessment).def: Coordinating the interaction of information from the eyes with body movement during activity

Visual Motor Integration (Treatment).def: Exercise or activities to facilitate coordinating the interaction of information from eyes with body movement during activity

Visual Reinforcement Audiometry.def: Behavioral measures using nonspeech and speech stimuli to obtain frequency/ear-specific information on auditory status
Visual Reinforcement Audiometry.inc: Includes a conditioned response of looking toward a visual reinforcer (e.g., lights, animated toy) every time auditory stimuli are heard

Vocational Activities and Functional Com.def: Measures environmental, home, work (job/school/play) barriers that keep patients from functioning optimally in their environment
Vocational Activities and Functional Com.inc: Includes assessment of vocational skill and interests, environment of work (job/school/play), injury potential and injury prevention or reduction, ergonomic stressors, transportation skills, and ability to access and use community resources

Vocational Activities and Functional Com.def: Activities to facilitate vocational exploration, body mechanics training, job acquisition, and environmental or work (job/school/play) task adaptation
Vocational Activities and Functional Com.inc: Includes injury prevention and reduction, ergonomic stressor reduction, job coaching and simulation, work hardening and conditioning, driving training, transportation skills,  and use of community resources

Voice (Assessment).def: Measures vocal structure, function and production

Voice (Treatment).def: Applying techniques to improve voice and vocal function

Voice Prosthetic (Assessment).def: Determines the appropriateness of voice prosthetic/adaptive device to enhance or facilitate communication

Wheelchair Mobility (Assessment).def: Measures fit and functional abilities within wheelchair in a variety of environments

Wheelchair Mobility (Treatment).def: Management, maintenance and controlled operation of a wheelchair, scooter or other device, in and on a variety of surfaces and environments

Biofeedback.def: Provision of information from the monitoring and regulating of physiological processes in conjunction with cognitive-behavioral techniques to improve patient functioning or well-being
Biofeedback.inc: Includes EEG, blood pressure, skin temperature or peripheral blood flow, ECG, electrooculogram, EMG, respirometry or capnometry, GSR/EDR, perineometry to monitor/regulate bowel/bladder activity, electrogastrogram to monitor/regulate gastric motility

Counseling.def: The application of psychological methods to treat an individual with normal developmental issues and psychological problems in order to increase function, improve well-being, alleviate distress, maladjustment or resolve crises

Crisis Intervention.def: Treatment of a traumatized, acutely disturbed or distressed individual for the purpose of short-term stabilization
Crisis Intervention.inc: Includes defusing, debriefing, counseling, psychotherapy and/or coordination of care with other providers or agencies

Electroconvulsive Therapy.def: The application of controlled electrical voltages to treat a mental health disorder
Electroconvulsive Therapy.inc: Includes appropriate sedation and other preparation of the individual

Family Psychotherapy.def: Treatment that includes one or more family members of an individual with a mental health disorder by behavioral, cognitive, psychoanalytic, psychodynamic or psychophysiological means to improve functioning or well-being
Family Psychotherapy.exp: Remediation of emotional or behavioral problems presented by one or more family members in cases where psychotherapy with more than one family member is indicated

Group Psychotherapy.def: Treatment of two or more individuals with a mental health disorder by behavioral, cognitive, psychoanalytic, psychodynamic or psychophysiological means to improve functioning or well-being

Hypnosis.def: Induction of a state of heightened suggestibility by auditory, visual and tactile techniques to elicit an emotional or behavioral response

Individual Psychotherapy.def: Treatment of an individual with a mental health disorder by behavioral, cognitive, psychoanalytic, psychodynamic or psychophysiological means to improve functioning or well-being

Light Therapy.def: Application of specialized light treatments to improve functioning or well-being

Medication Management.def: Monitoring and adjusting the use of medications for the treatment of a mental health disorder

Narcosynthesis.def: Administration of intravenous barbiturates in order to release suppressed or repressed thoughts

Psychological Tests.def: The administration and interpretation of standardized psychological tests and measurement instruments for the assessment of psychological function

Behavioral.inc: Includes modeling and role playing, positive reinforcement of target behaviors, response cost, and training of self-management skills

Cognitive.def: Primarily to correct cognitive distortions and errors

Cognitive-Behavioral.def: Combining cognitive and behavioral treatment strategies to improve functioning
Cognitive-Behavioral.exp: Maladaptive responses are examined to determine how cognitions relate to behavior patterns in response to an event. Uses learning principles and information-processing models

Developmental.def: Age-normed developmental status of cognitive, social and adaptive behavior skills

Intellectual and Psychoeducational.def: Intellectual abilities, academic   achievement and learning capabilities (including behaviors and emotional factors affecting learning

Interactive.def: Uses primarily physical aids and other forms of non-oral interaction with a patient who is physically, psychologically or developmentally unable to use ordinary language for communication
Interactive.inc: Includes. the use of toys in symbolic play

Interpersonal.def: Helps an individual make changes in interpersonal behaviors to reduce psychological dysfunction
Interpersonal.inc: Includes exploratory techniques, encouragement of affective expression, clarification of patient statements, analysis of communication patterns, use of therapy relationship and behavior change techniques

Neurobehavioral and Cognitive Status.def: Includes neurobehavioral status exam, interview(s), and observation for the clinical assessment of thinking, reasoning and judgment, acquired knowledge, attention, memory, visual spatial abilities, language functions, and planning

Neuropsychological.def: Thinking, reasoning and judgment, acquired knowledge, attention, memory, visual spatial abilities, language functions, planning

Personality and Behavioral.def: Mood, emotion, behavior, social functioning, psychopathological conditions, personality traits and characteristics

Psychoanalysis.def: Methods of obtaining a detailed account of past and present mental and emotional experiences to determine the source and eliminate or diminish the undesirable effects of unconscious conflicts
Psychoanalysis.exp: Accomplished by making the individual aware of their existence, origin, and inappropriate expression in emotions and behavior

Psychodynamic.def: Exploration of past and present emotional experiences to understand motives and drives using insight-oriented techniques to reduce the undesirable effects of internal conflicts on emotions and behavior
Psychodynamic.exp: Techniques include empathetic listening, clarifying self-defeating behavior patterns, and exploring adaptive alternatives

Psychophysiological.def: Monitoring and alteration of physiological processes to help the individual associate physiological reactions combined with cognitive and behavioral strategies to gain improved control of these processes to help the individual cope more effectively

Supportive.def: Formation of therapeutic relationship primarily for providing emotional support to prevent further deterioration in functioning during periods of particular stress
Supportive.exp: Often used in conjunction with other therapeutic approaches

Vocational.def: Exploration of vocational interests, aptitudes and required adaptive behavior skills to develop and carry out a plan for achieving a successful vocational placement
Vocational.inc: Includes enhancing work related adjustment and/or pursuing viable options in training education or preparation

Detoxification Services.exp: Not a treatment modality, but helps the patient stabilize physically and psychologically until the body becomes free of drugs and the effects of alcohol

Family Counseling.def: The application of psychological methods that includes one or more family members to treat an individual with addictive behavior
Family Counseling.exp: Provides support and education for family members of addicted individuals. Family member participation is seen as a critical area of substance abuse treatment

Group Counseling.def: The application of psychological methods to treat two or more individuals with addictive behavior
Group Counseling.exp: Provides structured group counseling sessions and healing power through the connection with others

Individual Counseling.def: The application of psychological methods to treat an individual with addictive behavior
Individual Counseling.exp: Comprised of several different techniques, which apply various strategies to address drug addiction

Individual Psychotherapy.def: Treatment of an individual with addictive behavior by behavioral, cognitive, psychoanalytic, psychodynamic or psychophysiological means

Medication Management.def: Monitoring and adjusting the use of replacement medications for the treatment of addiction

Pharmacotherapy.def: The use of replacement medications for the treatment of addiction

Assistance.def: Taking over a portion of a physiological function by extracorporeal means

Bypass.def: Altering the route of passage of the contents of a tubular body part

Destruction.def: Physical eradication of all or a portion of a body part by the direct use of energy, force, or a destructive agent
Destruction.exp: None of the body part is physically taken out
Destruction.inc: Fulguration of rectal polyp, cautery of skin lesion

Dilation.def: Expanding an orifice or the lumen of a tubular body part
Dilation.exp: The orifice can be a natural orifice or an artificially created orifice. Accomplished by stretching a tubular body part using intraluminal pressure or by cutting part of the orifice or wall of the tubular body part

Extirpation.def: Taking or cutting out solid matter from a body part
Extirpation.exp: The solid matter may be an abnormal byproduct of a biological function or a foreign body; it may be imbedded in a body part or in the lumen of a tubular body part. The solid matter may or may not have been previously broken into pieces

Fusion.def: Joining together portions of an articular body part rendering the articular body part immobile

Insertion.def: Putting in a nonbiological appliance that monitors, assists, performs, or prevents a physiological function but does not physically take the place of a body part

Inspection.def: Visually and/or manually exploring a body part

Introduction.def: Putting in or on a therapeutic, diagnostic, nutritional, physiological, or prophylactic substance except blood or blood products

Irrigation.def: Putting in or on a cleansing substance

Measurement.def: Determining the level of a physiological or physical function at a point in time

Monitoring.def: Determining the level of a physiological or physical function repetitively over a period of time

Other Procedures.def: Methodologies which attempt to remediate or cure a disorder or disease

Replacement.def: Putting in or on biological or synthetic material that physically takes the place and/or function of all or a portion of a body part

Reposition.def: Moving to its normal location, or other suitable location, all or a portion of a body part
Reposition.exp: The body part is moved to a new location from an abnormal location, or from a normal location where it is not functioning correctly. The body part may or may not be cut out or off to be moved to the new location
Reposition.inc: Reposition of undescended testicle, fracture reduction

Restriction.def: Partially closing an orifice or the lumen of a tubular body part

Supplement.def: Putting in or on biological or synthetic material that physically reinforces and/or augments the function of a portion of a body part

Transfusion.def: Putting in blood or blood products

External.def: Procedures performed directly on the skin or mucous membrane and procedures performed indirectly by the application of external force through the skin or mucous membrane

Open.def: Cutting through the skin or mucous membrane and any other body layers necessary to expose the site of the procedure

Percutaneous.def: Entry, by puncture or minor incision, of instrumentation through the skin or mucous membrane and any other body layers necessary to reach the site of the procedure

Percutaneous Endoscopic.def: Entry, by puncture or minor incision, of instrumentation through the skin or mucous membrane and any other body layers necessary to reach and visualize the site of the procedure

Via Natural or Artificial Opening.def: Entry of instrumentation through a natural or artificial external opening to reach the site of the procedure

Via Natural or Artificial Opening Endosc.def: Entry of instrumentation through a natural or artificial external opening to reach and visualize the site of the procedure
